text: Yep. So the biggest one, and to his credit, Lowe himself kind of identifies this as an area of ongoing work. And it was something, like I said, because of the proprietary database that at that point had been running for a decade, we had a lot of rich insights into this. It was just simply how, A, how different hedge fund strategies are very different betas. But then even within each of those strategies, the similarity of managers is much stronger than people realize. So it was kind of like two insights immediately rose to the top, which was long-short equity. And this is very intuitive to anybody that's been in the hedge fund space is long-short equity hedge funds are very different than stat-arb hedge funds. Yes, both of them are market neutral, let's say. Both of them are trading equities, but they're trafficking in different timeframes, they're employing different approaches, they're harvesting different factors. It's a totally different game. And so what we had been doing at the hedge fund, like I said, when we were running our manager due diligence reports, we were benchmarking or running attribution for every manager against their respective benchmark, which was an internal benchmark we created. And like I said, it wasn't just as simple as saying, all right, let's take the classifications. There was a lot of manual reclassifications, quantitative oversight, style drift. And so our long-short equity benchmark looked different enough from the off-the-shelf investment or HFRI benchmarks that there was power there and just kind of cleaning the data. And so that paper really did... There was kind of three... I don't know if it's three or four, but it was three or four. I don't know if it's three or three things in that paper. The first one was, we didn't want to go down the path of extending the math and running a lot of fancy different regressions. We had done that internally. It was an interesting exercise, continues to be, I think, in many respects. But what we wanted to do was introduce the idea of, let's keep the math relatively simple and more importantly, robust, but let's introduce a little more sophistication in the dependent variables. So let's keep the model the same, but let's point it at something that's a little more thoughtfully created. And so we had, I think, 10 different internal hedge funds that we had. And so we had, I think, hedge fund benchmarks that we manually created, updated every month. To give you an idea, we didn't even just look at long-short equity hedge funds. We classified it by long-short equity North America versus long-short equity EM versus sector focus. And so we wanted to make the dependent variables as homogenous as reasonable. And then the other thing we did was, as I said, we allowed the risk factors to A, be different by hedge fund asset class. So the risk factors that we'd be looking at for convertible bond arbitrage... Would obviously be different from the long-short equity funds. We incorporated a little bit of a stepwise process to allow there to be some variability in terms of looking at the different constellation of risk factors. And what we found was when you use that R-dependent variable, when you basically took Lowe's model and pointed it at what we would argue are a little bit more thoughtfully constructed hedge fund indices, as opposed to kind of an off-the-shelf version, that's when we saw the R-squareds just go massively up. And like I said, at the top of the list, I think on the first page or second page of that paper, we have an exhibit which maps or shows the out-of-sample R-squareds for all the different hedge fund strategies. And so at the top of the list, not surprisingly, is long-short equity North American hedge funds can 95% R-squared against a dynamic basket of tradable ETFs. Long and short, we constrain the regression to use no leverage. So again, all those problems of kind of just the original kind of hit the button and see what we get type factor attribution reports. We're developing this with the idea that, well, actually, at this point, we had already been, we'd been running, this paper came out at the end of 2011. So we'd already been running money in this portfolio for a year. And I'll come back to it, but we actually ended up getting a seed client, a big hospital foundation came in, seeded the strategy with $40 million. And by the time this paper came out, it was upwards of $100 million that we were running in the long-short equity North American clone portfolio. And I'll come back because 2011 was an interesting year in the hedge fund space, and it led to another paper that we wrote. But the other thing, which was kind of interesting, and it gets lost a little bit, but ostensibly the point of the paper we were writing in 2011 was it kind of presumed, okay, if you can realistically replicate certain hedge fund strategies, then what is the price of the option that you give the manager if you're willing to accept less liquidity than the underlying? So the premise being that, all right, if I have access to, hypothetically, if I have access to a basket of actual long-short equity managers, which most institutional investors do, and you have access to a clone portfolio, well, one of them has daily liquidity, one of them doesn't. And let's assume that there's no difference statistically or minimal difference statistically between the two portfolios. I'll even acknowledge that there's potentially a difference, but let's just price that in or let's account for that. But let's isolate the optionality that you're giving the hedge fund manager by accepting anything less than daily liquidity. And so we employed a bunch of options math to kind of price that out. And the number, not surprisingly, was high. Depending on kind of where in the matrix where you wanted liquidity, what you were giving up. But like I said, that was kind of secondary to the fact we started getting a lot of interest in the fact that people were saying, wait a second, the options application is kind of interesting. But let's go back to these clone portfolios. Like, how are you doing this? Oh, by the way, you guys are actually managing real money doing this. 2011 was an interesting year because long-short equity funds, depending on the index that you look at, were down between 6% and 8%. Our clone portfolio, which for most of that year was over $40 million, I think it was down 20, 25 basis points or something after fees, which was also another big point is we were charging, I think, 50 basis points or less than 50 basis points for that product. It was running an SMA for this big hospital foundation, full transparency. Interestingly, I don't want to go off on too much of a tangent, but they were huge. I mean, I think they had several billion dollars just in long-short equity funds. And they said they found the most utility. They liked it for a lot of reasons. They could use it for cash. They kind of used it as an ATM machine so they could access cash inter-month. They could use it as a placeholder after identifying a manager that they liked but couldn't yet send a subscription into. But they also used it as a real money benchmark to go back to their active guys and say, listen, your tariff sheet is saying that you have all this alpha relative to the S&P 500. However, you don't have any alpha or negative alpha relative to this clone portfolio. And they'd say, yeah, but that's not investable. And they'd say, well, no, actually it is. We have $80 million in it. We need to... We need to either benchmark your fees relative to this or have a conversation about fees. And that was something that was interesting to me because that hadn't really occurred to me as a use for a big institutional investor. But it was one that they were... It was utility that they were clearly seeing over and above just the mathematical appeal of the clone portfolio itself. Yeah.
